Let `Œ≥` be a countably generated measurable space and `Œ∫ Œ∑ : kernel Œ± Œ≥` be finite kernels. We build a function `rnDeriv Œ∫ Œ∑ : Œ± ‚Üí Œ≥ ‚Üí ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû` jointly measurable on `Œ± √ó Œ≥` and a kernel `singularPart Œ∫ Œ∑ : kernel Œ± Œ≥` such that `Œ∫ = withDensity Œ∑ (rnDeriv Œ∫ Œ∑) + singularPart Œ∫ Œ∑` and for all `a : Œ±`, `singularPart Œ∫ Œ∑ a ‚üÇ‚Çò Œ∑ a` .

Could you comment a little bit more on the implementation? (And in particular on the countably generated assumption, which is not relevant for the Radon-Nikodym theorem for measures but becomes necessary here unless I am mistaken).

I added comments about the implementation and the assumption. I was not sure whether that precise countability assumption was necessary. The only reference I can find says it is, but without proof: in Probability and Stochastics, Cinlar states before theorem 4.44 that "the separability condition cannot be removed" (separability = our countably generated). There is no other comment on the question.

```suggestion
lemma add_left_iff {Œº‚ÇÅ Œº‚ÇÇ ŒΩ : Measure Œ±}
```
When variables can be deduced from both sides of an iff, they are typically implicit, as they can be obtained automatically when one rewrites in one direction or the other.

```suggestion
Let `Œ≥` be a countably generated measurable space and `Œ∫, Œ∑ : kernel Œ± Œ≥` be finite kernels.
```

maybe
```suggestion
irreducible_def rnDeriv (Œ∫ Œ∑ : kernel Œ± Œ≥) (a : Œ±) (x : Œ≥) : ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû :=
```
Just to hide forever the details of the messy construction from the kernel. It will force you to unfold by hand the definition in the first few proofs below, but I guess that once the API is done you will never use the bare definition again.

```suggestion
irreducible_def singularPart (Œ∫ Œ∑ : kernel Œ± Œ≥) [IsSFiniteKernel Œ∫] [IsSFiniteKernel Œ∑] :
```

```suggestion
    singularPart Œ∫ Œ∑ a s = 0 :=
  measure_mono_null hs (singularPart_compl_mutuallySingularSetSlice Œ∫ Œ∑ a)
```
No need for `by exact`, except in rare exotic situations.

```suggestion
lemma withDensity_rnDeriv_of_subset_mutuallySingularSetSlice [IsFiniteKernel Œ∫]
```
Otherwise, it sounds as iff `withDensity_rnDeriv` was a subset of something (which doesn't make sense, of course). Same thing in the next lemma.
